{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653416"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:47:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:47:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18585"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18585"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11317"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79943"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11317"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18585"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65239"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10398"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26226"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26231"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79943"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDelta waves are characteristic electrical patterns recorded on electroencephalography (EEG) during certain stages of sleep.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the characteristics of delta waves?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Low amplitude, high frequency waves","High amplitude, low frequency waves","High amplitude, high frequency waves","Low amplitude, low frequency waves","Medium amplitude, medium frequency waves"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh amplitude, low frequency waves\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes delta waves, which have an amplitude greater than 75 microvolts and a frequency between 0.5-4 Hz. These waves are predominantly seen during stages 3 and 4 of non-rapid eye movement sleep, also known as slow-wave sleep.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow amplitude, high frequency waves\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes beta waves (13-30 Hz) seen during normal wakefulness\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh amplitude, high frequency waves\u003C/strong\u003E - This pattern would be more consistent with seizure activity\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow amplitude, low frequency waves\u003C/strong\u003E - This combination is not characteristic of any normal brain wave pattern\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedium amplitude, medium frequency waves\u003C/strong\u003E - This better describes alpha waves (8-13 Hz) seen during relaxed wakefulness\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDelta waves represent synchronised firing of large groups of thalamocortical neurons. While normal during deep sleep, their presence during wakefulness suggests pathology such as structural brain lesions or metabolic encephalopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Delta waves are high amplitude (\u003E75 microvolts), low frequency (0.5-4 Hz) brain waves seen during deep sleep.","Delta waves originate from synchronous firing of thalamocortical neurons during stage 3-4 non-rapid eye movement sleep.","Delta waves are normal in healthy adults during deep sleep but are abnormal when present during wakefulness."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65239"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18585"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65239"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-16T15:30:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-16T15:32:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11317"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79943"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{